label("$6$",(B+C)/2,NE);
label("$7$",(A+C)/2,NW);
[/asy] The length of the perimeter of $\triangle ABC$ is $5+6+7=18$. Therefore, each bug crawls $9$ units before reaching $D$. We draw $BD$ and label it $x$. By the Law of Cosines on $\triangle ABC$, we have \begin{align*}
BD^2 &= AB^2 + AD^2 - 2\cdot AB\cdot AD\cdot \cos \angle B \\
&= 5^2 + (9-x)^2 - 2\cdot 5\cdot (9-x)\cdot \cos \angle B \\
&= x^2 + (3)^2 - 2\cdot x\cdot 3\cdot \cos \angle B.
\end{align*} Also, by the Law of Cosines on $\triangle BCD$, we have \begin{align*}
BD^2 &= BC^2 + CD^2 - 2\cdot BC\cdot CD\cdot \cos \angle B \\
&= 6^2 + (x+3)^2 - 2\cdot 6\cdot (x+3)\cdot \cos \angle B \\
&= x^2 + (3)^2 + 2\cdot x\cdot 3\cdot \cos \angle B.
\end{align*} Equating these two expressions for $BD^2$, we have $x^2 + (3)^2 - 2\cdot x\cdot 3\cdot \cos \angle B = x^2 + (3)^2 + 2\cdot x\cdot 3\cdot \cos \angle B$, which simplifies to $4x=18\cdot 2$, so $x=\boxed{\frac{9}{2}}$.
